 "Report"}, "hash": "e8c793d02a3dafe66102f864fd1fb52cc19460a66f1adaefccd7b0ad28ad68e7"}, "3": {"node_id": "a30c2019-9abc-47c2-adf1-253247ffc2c8", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/natural-world-heritage-africa", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "93d5ad857627ee9a9dbd531b540a4347e1d1642f8d08d676e22a00babb197680"}}, "hash": "a77209575f3b0a79423aae1df5d29626f3a0bdaa3952d45936fc10870790ef49", "text": "(1) (2) (3) (5) (11) 081 Annob\u00f3n, 082 S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9, 083 Pr\u00edncipe, 086 Cameroon Mountains Guinean Forests of West Africa Congolian Coastal Forests, Cameroon Highland Forest, Gulf of Guinea Rivers and Streams Vall\u00e9e de Mai; Atsinanana; Gal\u00e1pagos; Teide; Aeolian Islands; Mount Etna; Hawaii; Ta\u00ef; Dja; Rwenzori; Bwindi; Kahuzi-Biega NATURAL WORLD HERITAGE IN AFRICA: PROGRESS AND PROSPECTS 64 3.4 Opportunities for extension and consolidation of existing sites In addition to new nominations, there are important opportunities for extension of some existing sites, as shown in the map in Figure 10 and detailed in Box 3. Some of these extensions have already been the subject of Committee Decisions. These are sometimes made at the time of inscription as a result of observations during the evaluation process, or may arise from reactive monitoring missions. Other possible extensions are included here on the basis of the authors\u2019 knowledge of each site. The aim would be to build on the initial inscription by either: (a) including important areas of adjacent habitat to enhance the site\u2019s ecological integrity and resilience within a wider landscape or seascape, or (b) for serial extensions, including important complimentary components that would provide a more complete representation of the attributes that contribute to the site\u2019s OUV. In some cases the proposed extensions are clearly challenging, long-term, ambitious and visionary, but they nevertheless deserve a place on the agenda for World Heritage on the continent. Photo: Giant Senecio plants, Mount Kenya National Park/Natural Forest, Kenya TOWARDS AN AGENDA FOR THE 2020s 65 Barberton Makhonjwa Mountains (South Africa). It was recognized at the time of inscription (2018) that this geological site would benefi t from extension to encompass additional areas, possibly also in Swaziland, in order to better refl ect the site\u2019s OUV. See Committee Decision 42 COM 8B.5 at http://whc. unesco.org/en/decisions/7118 Djoudj National Bird Sanctuary (Senegal). Situated in the Senegal River delta, the Djoudj sanctuary is a 16,000 ha wetland, comprising a large lake surrounded by streams, ponds and backwaters. It forms a living but fragile sanctuary for some 1.5 million birds including white pelican, purple heron, African spoonbill, great egret and great cormorant. The site would benefi t from transboundary extension to include Mauritania\u2019s adjacent Diawling National Park (the two protected areas are already cooperating within the framework of the UNESCO Man and the Biosphere (MAB) Programme as the Senegal River Delta Biosphere Reserve). See the 1985 Committee Decision CONF 008 XIII.A at: https://whc.unesco.org/en/decisions/3875/ Ennedi Massif: Natural and Cultural Landscape (Chad). It was recognized at the time of inscription (2016) that this site would benefi t from extension to incorporate adjacent areas that were included in the original nomination, but had to be excluded from the inscribed area as they were unduly threatened at the time. As these threats have subsequently abated, the additional areas should be added, thereby providing additional protection to a signifi cantly larger wilderness area. See Committee Decisions 40 COM 8B.15 at: https://whc.unesco.org/en/decisions/6793/ iSimangaliso Wetland Park (South Africa). This park covers extensive areas of wetland from the Lake St Lucia estuary northwards to the Mozambique border, incorporating extensive areas of coastal dunes and offshore marine reserves. The ecological integrity of this coastal wetland system could be enhanced through better transboundary coordination with similar protected areas in Mozambique, including extension of the existing World Heritage Site. See the 1999 Committee Decision CONF 209 VIII.A.1 at: https://whc.unesco.org/en/decisions/2548 Kenya Lake System in the Great Rift Valley (Kenya). The existing World Heritage Site (WHS) covers just three of the 10-12 \u2018fl amingo lakes\u2019 in the central portion of Africa\u2019s Great Rift Valley.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a30c2019-9abc-47c2-adf1-253247ffc2c8": {"__data__": {"id_": "a30c2019-9abc-47c2-adf1-253247ffc2c8", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/natural-world-heritage-africa", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Natural World Heritage in Africa", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/natural-world-heritage-africa", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e8c793d02a3dafe66102f864fd1fb52cc19460a66f1adaefccd7b0ad28ad68e7"}, "2": {"node_id": "d294b975-d137-4286-89ae-c75f6aafc419", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/natural-world-heritage-africa", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a77209575f3b0a79423aae1df5d29626f3a0bdaa3952d45936fc10870790ef49"}}, "hash": "93d5ad857627ee9a9dbd531b540a4347e1d1642f8d08d676e22a00babb197680", "text": "The fl amingo lakes are saline alkaline lakes, the environmental conditions of each changing cyclically depending on localised rainfall and other climatic factors, producing relatively short-lived algal blooms. The fl amingos take advantage of these cyclical changes in food supply and habitat conditions by moving between lakes, so the existing WHS is insuffi cient in itself to ensure the protection and integrity of the itinerant fl amingo population (which is the primary element of the site\u2019s OUV). The fl amingos main nesting site is Tanzania\u2019s Lake Natron, while the fl ocks also move south to Lakes Manyara and Eyasi and northwards into the southern parts of Ethiopia, notably Lakes Abijatta, Shalla, Metehara, Chitu, and Aranguade. Ideally, as many as possible of these lakes should be incorporated into an extended WHS, with extension to include the Lake Natron breeding area being especially important. See Committee Decision 35 COM 8B.6 at: https://whc.unesco.org/en/decisions/4277 OPPORTUNITIES FOR EXTENSION OF EXISTING SITES BOX 3 15 17 10 12 4 NATURAL WORLD HERITAGE IN AFRICA: PROGRESS AND PROSPECTS 66 Kilimanjaro National Park (Tanzania). Kilimanjaro", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "84c0099f-47ab-496f-9108-b429af93da4d": {"__data__": {"id_": "84c0099f-47ab-496f-9108-b429af93da4d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/natural-world-heritage-africa", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Natural World Heritage in Africa", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/natural-world-heritage-africa", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a02d35e43e400d667f2695cab18afc9d91482f43a11d42a3f583512acc3c11be"}, "3": {"node_id": "a4cdb891-f7f9-40aa-89bb-d669a65043bd", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/natural-world-heritage-africa", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c61ce75285a3c6c4a2dcd0431cdbcb8da0580992549c51ba61ed13558d0682bf"}}, "hash": "ac43b7819b4f521fe39c45ca36232c917cc85b6d1b21c25e7b9c8685bff085e7", "text": "National Park was extended in 2005 to incorporate much of the remaining montane forest on the mountain slopes, previously designated as forest reserve. The World Heritage Site boundaries pre-date this extension and cover only the summit of the mountain above 2,700m with six access corridors through the forested lower slopes. In order to improve the ecological integrity of the site it would be benefi cial to extend it to coincide with the new boundaries of the national park. See the 1987 Committee Decision CONF 005 VII.A at: https://whc.unesco.org/en/decisions/3754/ Lake Malawi National Park (Malawi). The small existing WHS in Malawi would benefi t from a serial extension to encompass additional shoreline areas elsewhere, particularly along the northern and eastern shores of the lake (in Tanzania and Mozambique) to more fully represent the extraordinary cichlid evolutionary radiation. The extension would recognise the fact that many cichlid varieties and species (as well as other taxa) have evolved in isolation in very restricted geographical localities around the lake. See Committee Decision 42 COM 7B.93 at: https://whc.unesco.org/en/decisions/7322/ Mana Pools National Park, Sapi and Chewore Safari Areas (Zimbabwe). Mana Pools forms part of a transboundary conservation complex that extends across the Zambezi Valley into Zambia\u2019s Lower Zambezi National Park (LZNP). Whilst there were serious poaching problems on the Zambian side at the time Mana Pools was listed, these have now abated and it would improve the viability and integrity of the conservation complex if the WHS were extended to include LZNP. See Committee Decision 42 COM 7B.97 at: https://whc.unesco.org/en/decisions/7326/ Mount Kenya National Park/Natural Forest (Kenya). The existing WHS covers the higher slopes of the mountain from an elevation of about 2,000-2,400m to the summit (1,824 km2), together with a separate component comprising the Ngare Ndare Forest Reserve and the Lewa Wildlife Conservancy. This area (198 km2, at 2,200m to 1,700m) was added as a serial extension in 2013. The extension is (very tentatively) linked to the main block via a 9.8 km-long \u2018elephant corridor\u2019 that runs through commercial farmland that separates the two component parts. A further extension would seek to consolidate this link by expanding the elephant corridor (through necessary land acquisition) and perhaps incorporate other areas at lower elevations (particularly the Imenti Forest and areas on the southeast slopes of the mountain). A more visionary and ambitious extension could envisage the establishment of a corridor linking Mount Kenya with Meru National Park via the Imenti Forest and Nyambeni Hills. See for example Committee Decision 37 COM 8B.9 at https://whc.unesco.org/en/decisions/5125 Niokolo-Koba National Park (Senegal). Niokolo-Koba is listed in Danger after losing much of its large mammal fauna to poaching, and will require a prolonged period of effective protection and management to allow for recovery. Nevertheless, its long-term ecological viability and prospects could be enhanced through the addition of Guinea\u2019s Badiar National Park. This is a contiguous area that includes important fl oodplain habitats along the Koulountou River. Okavango Delta (Botswana). The Okavango Delta is a large site that already includes signifi cant areas of mopane deciduous woodland bordering the delta. However, the maintenance of its remarkable seasonal fl ooding phenomenon depends on seasonal rains higher up the catchment in Angola\u2019s southern highlands. A transboundary extension of the site to protect this vital catchment area would bring signifi cant long- term benefi ts (see http://whc.unesco.org/en/events/1493/). Rainforests of the Atsinanana (Madagascar). The Rainforests of Atsinanana is a serial site with six components spread along the moist easterly \u2018spine\u2019 of Madagascar, with each component including numerous locally-endemic species of fl ora and fauna.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a4cdb891-f7f9-40aa-89bb-d669a65043bd": {"__data__": {"id_": "a4cdb891-f7f9-40aa-89bb-d669a65043bd", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/natural-world-heritage-africa", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Natural World Heritage in Africa", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/natural-world-heritage-africa", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a02d35e43e400d667f2695cab18afc9d91482f43a11d42a3f583512acc3c11be"}, "2": {"node_id": "84c0099f-47ab-496f-9108-b429af93da4d", "node_type": null, "metad